    <stitle>10 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER AUTOMATE-2 - REMOVE - OPTIONAL RANGE CASE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="9">
        <title>OPTIONAL RANGE CASE</title>
        <svcsubproc id="x1302201">
            <title>PROCEDURE FOR CONVENTIONAL VEHICLES</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is possible to service the range case without removing the entire transmission from the
                        vehicle.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Turn off and bleed the air system to prevent air lines from whipping, which could cause
                        injury.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Begin by removing the electric speedometer sensor and 1/4 inch air lines (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302241">Figure 41</hotlnk>). Remove the end yoke or flange.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302241" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302241" filename="../figg13/G1302241.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 41. Electric Speedometer Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the rear countershaft bearing cap and oil cooler pump assembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302242">Figure 42</hotlnk>). Also remove the oil cooler pump hose. Doing this will
                    allow clearance for the range case support fixture.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302242" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302242" filename="../figg13/G1302242.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Rear Countershaft Bearing Cap</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove all range case bolts except one at the top of the case (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302243">Figure 43</hotlnk>). Then secure the range case support fixture (ZTSE4278)
                    and a transmission jack stand to the unit. Secure the bracket to the output shaft using the output
                    washer and nut. Tighten the nut to 550 to 600 ft-lbs. (745 to 813 N&#183; m).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302243" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302243" filename="../figg13/G1302243.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 43. Range Case Bolt Removal</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the range section from the rest of the unit (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302244">Figure 44</hotlnk>). It may be helpful to use pry bars in the case slots
                    to separate the range case from the main case. Pull the range section straight off. It must be level
                    with the rest of the unit.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302244" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302244" filename="../figg13/G1302244.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 44. Range Section Removal</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">These parts can be serviced without removing the entire transmission completely from the
                    vehicle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302245">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302245" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302245" filename="../figg13/G1302245.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 45. Serviceable Parts</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">During reassembly, use alignment studs (7-inch length, 1/2-inch diameter) to make proper
                    installation easier (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302246">Figure 46</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302246" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302246" filename="../figg13/G1302246.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Use Alignment Studs</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="x1302202">
            <title>PROCEDURE FOR CABOVER VEHICLES</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is possible to service the range case without removing the entire transmission from the
                        vehicle.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Turn off and bleed the air system to prevent air lines from whipping, which could cause
                        injury.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the 1/4 inch air lines, the rear countershaft bearing cap and oil cooler pump
                    assembly, and the oil cooler pump hose (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302247">Figure 47</hotlnk>). Remove the end yoke or flange.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302247" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302247" filename="../figg13/G1302247.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Removal Procedure For Cabover</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the final case bolt and pull the range section from the transmission (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302248">Figure 48</hotlnk>). It may be helpful to use pry bars in the case slots
                    to separate the range section from the main case.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302248" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302248" filename="../figg13/G1302248.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. Pull Range Case</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">These parts can be serviced without removing the entire unit completely from the vehicle
                    (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302249">Figure 49</hotlnk>). During reassembly, use alignment studs (7-inch
                    length, 1/2-inch diameter) to make proper installation easier.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1302249" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302249" filename="../figg13/G1302249.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 49. Serviceable Parts</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
